revision.text:
{{Infobox hieroglyphs|TITEL=Zwölfte Tagesstunde|name=<hiero>M16-G1-p-D45:r-t:N5</hiero>|NAME-TRANSKRIPTION=Hapu-seret <br /> ''Ḥ3pw-srt'' <br /> ''Die den [[Re (Ägyptische Mythologie)|Glänzenden]] verbirgt''}}In [[Ancient Egypt|ancient Egypt,]] the '''{{ill|twelfth Hour (Ancient Egypt)|lt=12th Hour|de|Zwölfte Tagesstunde (Altes Ägypten|simple|User:Immanuelle/Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt) }}''' of the day (also '''twelfth hour of the day, "setting of Re in the west"''' ) was the twelfth hour of the day and was the "hour of [[sunset]] ", which ended with the beginning of [[Twilight|evening twilight]] ( {{Ill|First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|lt=First night hour|de|Erste Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|simple|User:Immanuelle/First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|en}} ).

In ancient Egypt, the times of day were represented by the {{ill|Hour deities|lt=hour goddesses|de|Stundengottheiten}} . The twelfth hour of the day was called “That which hides the shining one (Re)” and appears, among other places, in the “ {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en}} ” with the title “ ''The setting of this god (Re) in the Westland'' ”. From the explanations regarding the {{Ill|Amduat|4=de|6=en}}, it can be seen that at the end of the twelfth hour of the day, when [[Ra|Re]] begins to sink below the horizon, he is in the region of the {{Ill|Qenqenet|4=de|6=en}}, immediately in front of the “gateway to the [[Duat]] ”.

== See also ==

* {{ill|First Hour (Ancient Egypt)|lt=1st Hour|de|Erste Tagesstunde (Altes Ägypten)|simple|User:Immanuelle/First Hour (Ancient Egypt)}}
* {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day}}

== literature ==

* {{Ill|Christian Leitz|4=de}} : ''Ancient Egyptian star clocks'' . Peeters, Leuven 1995, ISBN 9-0683-1669-9 .
* Jürgen Osing: ''Hieratic papyri from Tebtunis I'' . Museum Tusculanum Press, Copenhagen 1998, ISBN 8-7728-9280-3 .
* {{Ill|Alexandra von Lieven|4=de}} : ''Outline of the course of the stars – The so-called Nutbook'' . The Carsten Niebuhr Institute of Ancient Eastern Studies (u.&nbsp;a.), Copenhagen 2007, ISBN 978-87-635-0406-5 .

{{draft categories|[[Category:History of timekeeping]][[fr:User:{{PAGENAME}}]]}}

{{Infobox hieroglyphs|TITEL=Twelfth hour of the day|name=<hiero>M16-G1-p-D45:r-t:N5</hiero>|NAME-TRANSKRIPTION=Hapu-seret <br /> ''Ḥ3pw-srt'' <br /> ''That hides the [[Ra|shining one]]''}}{{complex}}
