In [[Ancient Egypt|ancient Egypt,]] the '''{{ill|Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|lt=12th Hour|de|Zwölfte Tagesstunde (Altes Ägypten|simple|User:Immanuelle/Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''' of the day (also '''twelfth hour of the day, "setting of Re in the west"''' ) was the twelfth hour of the day and was the "hour of [[sunset]] ", which ended with the beginning of [[Twilight|evening twilight]] ( {{ill||First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|lt=First night hour|de|Erste Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|simple|User:Immanuelle/First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|en}} ).

In ancient Egypt, the times of day were represented by the {{ill|Hour deities|lt=hour goddesses|de|Stundengottheiten|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} . The twelfth hour of the day was called “That which hides the shining one (Re)” and appears, among other places, in the “ {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ” with the title “ ''The setting of this god (Re) in the Westland'' ”. From the explanations regarding the {{ill||Amduat|4=de|6=en}}, it can be seen that at the end of the twelfth hour of the day, when [[Ra|Re]] begins to sink below the horizon, he is in the region of the {{ill||Qenqenet|4=de|6=pt}}, immediately in front of the “gateway to the [[Duat]] ”.

== See also ==

* {{ill|First hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|lt=1st Hour|de|Erste Tagesstunde (Altes Ägypten)|simple|User:Immanuelle/First hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}


