In ancient Egypt, the times of day were represented by the {{ill|Hour deities|lt=hour goddesses|de|Stundengottheiten|qq=draft}} . The twelfth hour of the day was called “That which hides the shining one (Re)” and appears, among other places, in the “ {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day|qq=draft}} ” with the title “ ''The setting of this god (Re) in the Westland'' ”. From the explanations regarding the {{ill|Amduat|4=de|6=en}}, it can be seen that at the end of the twelfth hour of the day, when [[Ra|Re]] begins to sink below the horizon, he is in the region of the {{ill|Qenqenet|4=de|6=pt}}, immediately in front of the “gateway to the [[Duat]] ”.

