In [[:en:Ancient Egypt|ancient Egypt,]] the '''{{ill|Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|lt=12th Hour|de|Zwölfte Tagesstunde (Altes Ägypten|simple|User:Immanuelle/Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Twelfth hour of the day (Ancient Egypt)|qq=}}''' of the day (also '''twelfth hour of the day, "setting of Re in the west"''' ) was the twelfth hour of the day and was the "hour of [[sunset]] ", which ended with the beginning of [[Twilight|evening twilight]] ( {{ill|First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|lt=First night hour|de|Erste Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|simple|User:Immanuelle/First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/First hour of the night (Ancient Egypt)|qq=}} ).

In ancient Egypt, the times of day were represented by the {{ill|Hour deities|lt=hour goddesses|de|Stundengottheiten|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hour deities|qq=}} . The twelfth hour of the day was called “That which hides the shining one (Re)” and appears, among other places, in the “ {{ill|Book of the Day|de|Buch des Tages|en|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Book of the Day|qq=}} ” with the title “ ''The setting of this god (Re) in the Westland'' ”. From the explanations regarding the {{ill|Amduat|4=de|6=en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amduat|qq=}}, it can be seen that at the end of the twelfth hour of the day, when [[Ra|Re]] begins to sink below the horizon, he is in the region of the {{ill|Qenqenet|4=de|6=pt|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Qenqenet|qq=}}, immediately in front of the “gateway to the [[:en:Duat|Duat]] ”.

